		<header>
			
			<h1>Major shake-up pending in Kenyan sugar sector?</h1>

			
			<h4>
												13 October 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In August 2013, Kenyan sugar millers claimed that they were unable to clear stocks of sugar “due to suspected dumping of duty-free sugar from Uganda and Tanzania”. It was maintained that “sugar imports from Uganda have increased from an all-time low of 73 tonnes reported in 2011 to more than 30,000 tonnes last year and more than 15,000 tonnes by July this year.”</p><p>These complaints followed an earlier dispute in 2012 in which the Kenyan authorities blocked sugar imports from Uganda and Tanzania. A joint secretariat was subsequently established to manage the special dispensation granted by the EAC, which allowed Uganda and Tanzania to import duty-free sugar from outside COMESA “to bridge a huge sugar shortage they were experiencing”. At the time, it was claimed that this dispensation had allowed the import of 40,000 tonnes, more than the 10,000 tonnes permitted with the duty waived. According to Kenyan millers, this resulted in imports from Uganda and Tanzania increasing tenfold, despite a reported 220,000 tonnes annual deficit in Tanzanian sugar production.</p><p>These imports, it was maintained, have led to a dramatic reduction in sugar prices paid to millers in the preceding 3 months and the accumulation of stocks, which delayed payments to farmers and led to losses being posted by the largest Kenyan sugar company, Mumias Sugar Company (MSC). Currently Kenyan officials are seeking a solution that would prevent sugar being exported from Uganda and Tanzania to Kenya within 6 months of such duty-free imports being allowed.</p><p>These problems, however, should be viewed against the 27% increase in operating costs of Kenyan sugar factories in the year to July 2013, which rose to US$700/tonne (compared to costs of US$300/tonne in Zambia, US$310/tonne in Malawi and US$340/tonnes in Swaziland and Sudan). Kenya’s minister of trade has painted a grim picture of the prospects for the Kenyan sugar sector, if the COMESA safeguard measures are removed as scheduled. The report suggests that, with the exception of MSC, “none of the other seven millers across the country will survive the expected influx of cheaper imports.” Privatisation is considered essential for getting to grips with the competitiveness challenges faced, with government favouring partnerships involving strategic investors, with shares for sugar cane farmers (24%) and government (25%). To date there has been little progress in privatisation.</p><p>With the March 2014 deadline for the lapsing of the COMESA sugar safeguard provisions looming, government officials have reportedly indicated that they will be seeking a further extension of the COMESA safeguards, given the enormous challenges still faced (this would make it the fifth extension).</p><p>In August 2013, it was announced that a further sugar mill was to be established by the Riana Sugar Company in competition with existing sugar millers, Sony Sugar, Sukari Industries and Trans Mara Sugar. Also in August, MSC announced the introduction of “early maturing cane varieties, a new fertiliser regime and re-modelled farmer service delivery channels in order to increase the area under cane and cane yields”; the establishment of “additional cane buying centres… to facilitate sugar cane collection” and reduce cane poaching; an expansion of production of branded sugar to increase MSC’s market share; and the introduction of bottled water production.</p><p>In September, meanwhile, financing was secured for the constructions of the mill, distillery and power plant at the Kwale International Sugar Company Limited (Kiscol) in the eastern coastal zone of Kenya. The location of the project is well suited to sugar production, while the engagement of the Mauritian sugar company Omnicane offers a strategic partner for the integrated development of the project. As the company will run its own estates in an area where there are no other millers, it is considered that cane poaching is unlikely to arise.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
