				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The establishment of new mills alongside existing millers is likely to increase competition for cane, and also cane poaching, and will probably result in reduced capacity utilisation and lower levels of corporate investment in cane production in areas where poaching is endemic. This suggests an urgent need to improve the way in which the domestic sugar supply chains function, including through strengthening contractual arrangements between sugar cane farmers and millers.</p><p>Closely related to this is the matter of increasing smallholder farmers’ productivity (by introducing higher-yielding cane varieties and irrigation) and improving cane delivery systems to improve sucrose extraction rates.</p><p>It is noteworthy that the largest new investment involving experienced foreign ‘strategic partners’ is estate-based and located in a zone ideally suited for cane production where problems of cane poaching do not arise. This suggests that unless problems linked to the functioning of sugar supply chains are addressed, foreign strategic partners are unlikely to be attracted to engaging in existing areas of sugar production in eastern Kenya.</p><p>Any further extension of COMESA sugar safeguards would be likely to further delay domestic sugar sector reforms and exacerbate tensions in both intra-EAC sugar trade and intra-COMESA sugar trade. The situation facing the Kenyan sugar sector is unlikely to be improved by further delays, given that from around 2020 expanded sugar production across Southern and Eastern Africa is likely to be seeking alternative markets, as the EU market becomes less and less attractive as an export destination (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Sugar/Impact-of-CAP-reform-agreement-on-the-sugar-sector" target="_blank">Impact of CAP reform agreement on the sugar sector</a>’, 6 August 2013).</p>
		</div>
		
